      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Read all safety warnings, instructions, illustrations and specifications provided with this power tool. Failure to follow all instructions may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury. Save all warnings and instructions for future reference.
      </div>

      <h3>Specific rules for jig saws</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hold the tool by the insulated gripping surfaces</strong> when the cutting accessory may contact hidden wiring. A blade contacting a live wire will energize exposed metal parts and can shock the operator. Check the work area for hidden gas pipes, electrical wires, and water pipes before making blind or plunge cuts.</li>
        <li><strong>Clamp or otherwise secure the workpiece</strong> to a stable platform. Holding work by hand or against your body leaves it unstable and can lead to loss of control.</li>
        <li>Keep hands away from all cutting edges and moving parts.</li>
        <li>Always wear eye protection marked to comply with ANSI Z87.1. In dusty work, wear appropriate respiratory protection or use an OSHA‑compliant dust extraction solution.</li>
        <li>Only use blades rated for the operating speed setting of the tool.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Battery safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use the tool only with its specifically designated M12&trade; battery packs, and recharge only with the M12&trade; charger.</li>
        <li>Keep an idle battery away from paper clips, coins, keys, nails, screws and other small metal objects that can short the terminals &mdash; shorting can cause burns or fire.</li>
        <li>Do not use a battery or tool that is damaged or modified. Do not expose a battery or tool to fire or temperatures above 265&deg;F (130&deg;C) &mdash; this may cause an explosion.</li>
        <li>Under abuse, liquid may be ejected from the battery; avoid contact and flush with water if contact occurs (seek medical help for eye contact).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        Some dust from sawing, sanding, grinding and drilling contains chemicals known to cause cancer, birth defects or reproductive harm (e.g. lead from lead‑based paint, crystalline silica from masonry, and arsenic/chromium from chemically‑treated lumber). Work in a well‑ventilated area and wear an approved dust mask designed to filter microscopic particles.
      </div>

