      <h2>Assembly &amp; Setup</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Before changing blades or accessories or making any adjustment, remove the battery pack to avoid starting the tool. Always remove the battery whenever the tool is not in use.
      </div>

      <h3>Removing / inserting the battery</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Remove:</strong> push in the release buttons and pull the battery pack away from the tool.</li>
        <li><strong>Insert:</strong> slide the pack into the body of the tool until it latches securely into place.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Installing saw blades</h3>
      <div class="note">Use only T‑shank jig saw blades.</div>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Firmly rotate the blade change lever as far as it will go and hold it in position.</li>
        <li>Fit the blade into the groove in the support roller and push it firmly into the plunger as far as it will go &mdash; the lug of the blade must seat in the plunger.</li>
        <li>Release the blade change lever; the blade is automatically held.</li>
        <li>Check that the blade is held firmly &mdash; the slot in the plunger will sit at an angle to the blade.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Installing the dust cover</h3>
      <p>The dust cover works with the vacuum attachment to seal dust around the front of the tool for more efficient collection.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Slide the cover onto the tool in the orientation shown until it clips in place.</li>
        <li>To remove, squeeze and pull it away from the tool.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">Do not use the dust cover when making bevel/angle cuts.</div>

      <h3>Using the anti‑splinter plate</h3>
      <p>The anti‑splinter plate helps stabilize the workpiece and reduce splintering.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Slide the anti‑splinter plate onto the shoe, flush with the bottom of the shoe.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">Do not use the anti‑splinter plate when making bevel/angle cuts.</div>

      <h3>Using the shoe cover</h3>
      <p>The shoe cover prevents marring and scratching of the workpiece surface.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Hook the front of the cover over the metal shoe.</li>
        <li>Snap the rear of the cover over the back of the shoe; make sure both sides are snapped in place.</li>
        <li>To remove, pull the tabs on the rear of the cover down, unhook the front, and lift it off.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">Two saw blades can be stored inside the shoe cover.</div>

      <h3>Adjusting the bevel angle</h3>
      <p>The shoe can tilt up to 45&deg; in either direction. Do not use the transparent blade cover or anti‑splinter plate when making bevel cuts.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Loosen the bevel adjusting screw with the onboard hex wrench.</li>
        <li>Hold the shoe and rotate the jig saw by the handle to the desired angle on the bevel scale.</li>
        <li>Tighten the bevel adjusting screw securely.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Vacuum hose adapter</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery.</li>
        <li>Slide the adapter into the jig saw and push them together firmly.</li>
        <li>Connect the vacuum hose to the adapter, twisting to secure.</li>
        <li>To remove, disconnect the hose, then grasp the saw and adapter firmly and pull apart.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always wear eye protection marked to comply with ANSI Z87.1. In dusty work, wear appropriate respiratory protection or use an OSHA‑compliant dust extraction solution.
      </div>

      <h3>Fuel gauge</h3>
      <p>Turn the tool ON to read the charge; the fuel gauge lights for 2&ndash;3 seconds.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>When less than 10% charge remains, one light flashes 4 times.</li>
        <li>At end of charge, one light flashes 8 times and the tool will not run &mdash; charge the pack.</li>
        <li>If the battery is too hot, the fuel gauge lights flash and the tool will not run &mdash; let the battery cool.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Sawdust blower</h3>
      <p>The sawdust blower clears dust ahead of the cut for better visibility and dust collection. Slide the switch one way to turn the blower ON and the other way to turn it OFF.</p>

      <h3>Starting and stopping</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>To start, slide the power switch to reveal &ldquo;I&rdquo;.</li>
        <li>The workpiece LED lights; press the LED button to toggle it on and off.</li>
        <li>To stop, slide the power switch to reveal &ldquo;O&rdquo;. Let the tool come to a complete stop before laying it down.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Selecting the speed</h3>
      <p>Turn the speed dial (1&ndash;5, plus <strong>A</strong> for auto‑controlled start) to set strokes per minute. 1 is slowest, 5 is fastest. Speed may be adjusted while running or stopped.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Speed setting</th><th>SPM</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1</td><td>800</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td>1,200</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td>1,800</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>2,500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>5</td><td>3,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>A</td><td>Starts at 1,500, rises to 3,000</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="warning">Only use saw blades rated for the operating speed setting of the tool.</div>

      <h3>Adjusting the orbital action</h3>
      <p>Set orbital action with the selector lever. In general, use a larger orbital action (4) on soft materials and no orbital action (0) on hard materials or when a smooth cut is required. Orbital action may be adjusted while running or stopped.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Material</th><th>Orbital action</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Wood</td><td>0&ndash;4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Metal</td><td>0&ndash;1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Aluminum</td><td>0&ndash;1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plastic</td><td>0&ndash;2</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Smooth cut</td><td>0</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Making the cut</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the speed and orbital action for the material to be cut.</li>
        <li>Position the front of the shoe on the workpiece, then start the tool.</li>
        <li>Hold the tool firmly against the workpiece and guide it along the cutting line. Do not feed too hard &mdash; light pressure achieves the optimum cutting speed.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Special cutting techniques</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Straight cuts</strong> &mdash; clamp a strip of wood as a guide along the workpiece, or use the rip guide (accessory).</li>
        <li><strong>Bevel cuts</strong> &mdash; adjust the shoe to the correct angle.</li>
        <li><strong>Sheet metal</strong> &mdash; sheet metal can vibrate when cut; clamp the workpiece to a wood base to minimize vibration.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        Do not start the tool with the blade contacting the workpiece. Make sure the blade extends beyond the shoe and workpiece throughout the stroke &mdash; blades may shatter if they impact the workpiece.
      </div>

      <h3>Plunge cutting</h3>
      <p>Plunge cuts can be made into soft materials without a pre‑drilled hole. Harder materials require a starter hole slightly wider than the blade.</p>
      <div class="danger">
        Always check the work area for hidden gas pipes, electrical wires and water pipes before making blind or plunge cuts.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the orbital action selector to 0.</li>
        <li>Make sure nothing below the cut area will be damaged.</li>
        <li>With the tool off, place the front edge of the shoe solidly on the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Align the blade with the cut line but keep it above the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Using the front edge of the shoe as a pivot, turn on the tool and gradually lower the blade into the workpiece.</li>
        <li>When the shoe is flat against the workpiece, proceed with normal cutting.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Remove the battery pack before performing any maintenance. Never disassemble the battery pack, charger or tool except as described in the manual &mdash; contact a Milwaukee service facility for all other repairs. Never immerse the tool, battery or charger in liquid.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Adopt a regular maintenance program. Inspect the tool for undue noise, misalignment or binding of moving parts, broken parts, or any other condition affecting operation.</li>
        <li>After six months to one year (depending on use), return the tool, battery and charger to a Milwaukee service facility for inspection.</li>
        <li><strong>Cleaning:</strong> clear dust and debris from vents. Keep the tool clean, dry and free of oil and grease. Use only mild soap and a damp cloth &mdash; solvents such as gasoline, turpentine, lacquer/paint thinner, chlorinated solvents, ammonia, and ammonia‑based detergents harm plastics and insulation. Never use flammable or combustible solvents around the tool.</li>
        <li><strong>Accessories:</strong> use only recommended accessories; others may be hazardous. See www.milwaukeetool.com for the full list.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause / remedy</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Tool will not run; one fuel‑gauge light flashes 8 times</td><td>Battery is depleted &mdash; charge the M12&trade; battery pack.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool will not run; fuel‑gauge lights flash</td><td>Battery is too hot &mdash; allow it to cool before use.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>One fuel‑gauge light flashes 4 times</td><td>Less than 10% charge remaining &mdash; charge soon.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool does not start or lacks full power with a charged pack</td><td>Clean the contacts on the battery pack; if it still misbehaves, return tool, charger and battery to a Milwaukee service facility.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Blade not held / pops loose</td><td>Confirm a T‑shank blade is fully seated with its lug in the plunger; the plunger slot should sit at an angle to the blade.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Rough or splintered cut</td><td>Reduce orbital action toward 0, fit the anti‑splinter plate, and reduce feed pressure.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

